How much you get rewarded is based off how much value your model adds to the network, not the gpu you're running. ie. How accurately the model can make predictions (its 'loss'), and how unique the model is compared to the rest of the network.

If you're running a validator, you're rewarded proportionally to the amount of T you have staked to that hotkey. About 1.4 T rewarded / 1000T staked / day I think?
machine learning uses models which make predictions based on prior "training"
you can download pretrained models from huggingface very easily and get them running, so most people are doing that
you find a model on huggingface.co and copy it's name, then pass that in to your server `--neuron.model_name` and it will load it from huggingface
You serve a model on the network that gets requests from validators
these validators are validating, or verifying, that your model is capable of doing a machine learning task
this task is usually next token prediction (NTP) but it can be one of a few natural language processing (NLP) related tasks as well
the idea is that validators rank you in order for them to receive rewards and they are incentivized to rank you fairly
then you are incentivized to serve a good model as your ranking dictates your rewards
so then the network has an overall incentive of driving ML innovation and making the whole of the network better at the task (i.e. have a lower loss on the dataset)

so servers provide and run a model, validators try and rank that model

you're right... same as bitcoin.... as the number of miners increased from 1000 to 10,000 to 100,000 the amount of bitcoin they were all going for remained the same (and in fact decreased with each halving)
but at 40,000 nodes, the network will be that much more valuable than at 4,000 nodes and it will be reflected in the price of Tao the same way it has been in BTC.
could you elaborate on this a bit? why exactly does an increase in nodes cause a rise in price? what factors would cause such relationship to occur?
also, when is the upgrade for that to occur scheduled?

examine the BTC case.... why are people still mining even though at 100k miners they are making 1/100th of the BTC that they could mine at 1k miners? It's called the network effect.... the value of a network is porportional to the square of it's participants.
(i don't know how many miners BTC has at the moment, above are just examples).
i suspect it's less scheduled than something that will come about when there is a need to expand.
ok

going from 4K UIDs to 10s of 1000s of UIDs is not a simple task by any stretch of imagination, there are engineering challenges that will need to be resolved before it's possible. At the same time there  won't be a need to jump from this to something extreme, it can grow as it has been.
any idea on how to go about forecasting what the drop in overall rewards will be? Will it actually be 1/10th since UID growth will be 10x?
exactly... if it takes place after the first halving in 2025 then would need to divide by 2 in addition.
rather ... when considering long term time-frame would also need to consider the halving and divide by 2 for anything after the halving event in 2025.... and so on.
